<taxonomicName authorityName="Plieninger" authorityYear="1901" box="[997,1176,1746,1772]" pageId="26" pageNumber="707" rank="superFamily" superFamily="Pterodactyloidea">Pterodactyloidea</taxonomicName>
indet. A
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="28" lastPageNumber="709" pageId="26" pageNumber="707" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="26.[997,1270,1746,1804]" box="[1063,1204,1778,1804]" pageId="26" pageNumber="707">
(
<figureCitation box="[1072,1148,1778,1804]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="27.[132,143,1940,1957]" captionTargetBox="[132,1455,215,1878]" captionTargetId="figure-23@27.[698,1267,768,1324]" captionTargetPageId="27" captionText="FIG. 20. — Pterosaur teeth from Angeac-Charente:A, Pterodactyloidea indet.A (ANG M-24) in labial view;B, Pterodactyloidea indet.A (ANG M-10) in lingual view; C, D, Pterodactyloidea indet. A, (ANG M-42) in lingual (C) and mesial (D) views; E, F, Pterodactyloidea indet. B, (ANG M-43) in lingual (E) and mesial (F) views; G, H, Pterodactyloidea indet. B, (ANG M-112) in lingual (G) and mesial (H) views; I, Pterodactyloidea indet. B, (ANG M-40) in lingual view; J, K, Pterosauria indet. (ANG M-41) in labial (J) and distal (K) views; L, M, Pterosauria indet. (ANG M-113) in lingual (L) and mesial (M) views. Scale bar: 500 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6902083" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6902083/files/figure.png" pageId="26" pageNumber="707">Fig. 20</figureCitation>
A-D)
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="26.[810,1457,1842,2028]" box="[813,952,1842,1868]" pageId="26" pageNumber="707">DESCRIPTION</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="26.[810,1457,1842,2028]" lastBlockId="28.[130,776,215,656]" lastPageId="28" lastPageNumber="709" pageId="26" pageNumber="707">
This indeterminate pterodactyloid taxon is represented by small, labiolingually compressed teeth (
<figureCitation box="[1167,1243,1905,1931]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="27.[132,143,1940,1957]" captionTargetBox="[132,1455,215,1878]" captionTargetId="figure-23@27.[698,1267,768,1324]" captionTargetPageId="27" captionText="FIG. 20. — Pterosaur teeth from Angeac-Charente:A, Pterodactyloidea indet.A (ANG M-24) in labial view;B, Pterodactyloidea indet.A (ANG M-10) in lingual view; C, D, Pterodactyloidea indet. A, (ANG M-42) in lingual (C) and mesial (D) views; E, F, Pterodactyloidea indet. B, (ANG M-43) in lingual (E) and mesial (F) views; G, H, Pterodactyloidea indet. B, (ANG M-112) in lingual (G) and mesial (H) views; I, Pterodactyloidea indet. B, (ANG M-40) in lingual view; J, K, Pterosauria indet. (ANG M-41) in labial (J) and distal (K) views; L, M, Pterosauria indet. (ANG M-113) in lingual (L) and mesial (M) views. Scale bar: 500 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6902083" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6902083/files/figure.png" pageId="26" pageNumber="707">Fig. 20</figureCitation>
A-D). The crown is relatively low, triangular and broad-based in labial and lingual views (
<figureCitation box="[882,953,1969,1995]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="27.[132,143,1940,1957]" captionTargetBox="[132,1455,215,1878]" captionTargetId="figure-23@27.[698,1267,768,1324]" captionTargetPageId="27" captionText="FIG. 20. — Pterosaur teeth from Angeac-Charente:A, Pterodactyloidea indet.A (ANG M-24) in labial view;B, Pterodactyloidea indet.A (ANG M-10) in lingual view; C, D, Pterodactyloidea indet. A, (ANG M-42) in lingual (C) and mesial (D) views; E, F, Pterodactyloidea indet. B, (ANG M-43) in lingual (E) and mesial (F) views; G, H, Pterodactyloidea indet. B, (ANG M-112) in lingual (G) and mesial (H) views; I, Pterodactyloidea indet. B, (ANG M-40) in lingual view; J, K, Pterosauria indet. (ANG M-41) in labial (J) and distal (K) views; L, M, Pterosauria indet. (ANG M-113) in lingual (L) and mesial (M) views. Scale bar: 500 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6902083" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6902083/files/figure.png" pageId="26" pageNumber="707">Fig. 20</figureCitation>
A-C). The basal part of the labial and lingual faces is devoid of enamel, except along the mesial and distal carinae. The crown base is slightly inflated and the recurved apex is more or less slender, so that in labial view the carinae are convex and concave in the basal half and distal half of the crown,respectively. A weak enamel ornamentation consisting of faint vertical folds is present in some teeth. This taxon, characterized by a gradual heterodonty, corresponds to the morphotypes 5-7 reported from the Purbeckian beds of Chassiron (
<bibRefCitation author="VULLO R. &amp; ABIT D. &amp; BALLEVRE M. &amp; BILLON- BRUYAT J. - P. &amp; BOURGEAIS R. &amp; BUFFETAUT E. &amp; DAVIERO- GOMEZ V. &amp; GARCIA G. &amp; GOMEZ B. &amp; MAZIN J. - M. &amp; MOREL S. &amp; NERAUDEAU D. &amp; POUECH J. &amp; RAGE J. - C. &amp; SCHNYDER J. &amp; TONG H." box="[499,674,406,433]" journalOrPublisher="Comptes Rendus Palevol" pageId="28" pageNumber="709" pagination="421 - 441" part="13" refId="ref50388" refString="VULLO R., ABIT D., BALLEVRE M., BILLON- BRUYAT J. - P., BOURGEAIS R., BUFFETAUT E., DAVIERO- GOMEZ V., GARCIA G., GOMEZ B., MAZIN J. - M., MOREL S., NERAUDEAU D., POUECH J., RAGE J. - C., SCHNYDER J. &amp; TONG H. 2014. - Palaeontology of the Purbeck-type (Tithonian, Late Jurassic) bonebeds of Chassiron (Oleron Island, western France). Comptes Rendus Palevol 13: 421 - 441. https: // doi. org / 10.1016 / j. crpv. 2014.03.003" title="Palaeontology of the Purbeck-type (Tithonian, Late Jurassic) bonebeds of Chassiron (Oleron Island, western France)" type="journal article" year="2014">
Vullo 
<emphasis box="[563,613,406,432]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="709">et al.</emphasis>
2014
</bibRefCitation>
: fig. 17eg) and to the isolated tooth MPZ2011/46 described from the Valanginian-Hauterivian of Pochancalo 
<quantity box="[538,578,470,496]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.54" pageId="28" pageNumber="709" unit="in" value="1.0">1 in</quantity>
northeastern 
<collectingCountry box="[716,775,470,496]" name="Spain" pageId="28" pageNumber="709">Spain</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Gasca" box="[140,306,502,528]" etAl="et al." firstAuthor="Gasca" pageId="28" pageNumber="709" pagination="159 - 172" refId="ref40369" refString="GASCA J. M., BADIOLA A., CANUDO J. I., MORENO- AZANZA M. &amp; PUERTOLAS E. 2012. - La asociacion de vertebrados fosiles del yacimiento Pochancalo 1 (Valanginiense-Hauteriviense, Villanueva de Huerva, Zaragoza, Espana), in Actas de V Jornadas Internacionales sobre Paleontologia de Dinosaurios y su Entorno. Salas de los Infantes, Burgos: 159 - 172." type="book chapter" year="2012">
Gasca 
<emphasis box="[204,250,502,528]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="709">et al.</emphasis>
2012
</bibRefCitation>
:fig.3k).Since this tooth morphology is present in some archaeopterodactyloids (e.g., 
<taxonomicName box="[516,646,534,560]" class="Reptilia" family="Pterodactylidae" genus="Pterodactylus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" pageId="28" pageNumber="709" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[516,646,534,560]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="709">Pterodactylus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Young" authorityYear="1964" class="Reptilia" family="Germanodactylidae" genus="Germanodactylus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" pageId="28" pageNumber="709" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="709">Germanodactylus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) and istiodactyliforms (e.g., 
<taxonomicName authority=", Longchengopterus, Mimodactylus" authorityName="Longchengopterus, Mimodactylus" class="Reptilia" genus="Haopterus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" pageId="28" pageNumber="709" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[481,582,567,592]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="709">Haopterus</emphasis>
, 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="709">Longchengopterus, Mimodactylus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) (
<bibRefCitation author="Lu" box="[296,440,598,624]" etAl="et al." firstAuthor="Lu" pageId="28" pageNumber="709" pagination="229 - 241" refId="ref42667" refString="LU J., XU L. &amp; JI Q. 2008. - Restudy of Liaoxipterus (Istiodactylidae: Pterosauria), with comments on the Chinese istiodactylid pterosaurs. Zitteliana B 28: 229 - 241. https: // doi. org / 10.5282 / ubm / epub. 12018" type="journal article" year="2008">
Lü 
<emphasis box="[331,381,598,624]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="709">et al.</emphasis>
2008
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="WANG X. &amp; CAMPOS D. A. &amp; ZHOU Z. &amp; KELLNER A. W. A." box="[453,630,598,624]" journalOrPublisher="Zootaxa" pageId="28" pageNumber="709" part="1813" refId="ref50554" refString="WANG X., CAMPOS D. A., ZHOU Z. &amp; KELLNER A. W. A. 2008. - A primitive istiodactylid pterosaur (Pterodactyloidea) from the Jiufotang Formation (Early Cretaceous), Northeast China. Zootaxa 1813: https: // doi. org / 1 - 18. 10.5281 / zenodo. 274343" title="A primitive istiodactylid pterosaur (Pterodactyloidea) from the Jiufotang Formation (Early Cretaceous), Northeast China" type="journal volume" year="2008">
Wang 
<emphasis box="[521,571,598,624]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="709">et al.</emphasis>
2008
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Kellner" etAl="et al." firstAuthor="Kellner" pageId="28" pageNumber="709" pagination="1 - 9" refId="ref41962" refString="KELLNER A. W. A., CALDWELL M. W., HOLGADO B., DALLA VECCHIA F. M., NOHRA R., SAYAO J. M. &amp; CURRIE P. J. 2019. - First complete pterosaur from the Afro-Arabian continent: insight into pterodactyloid diversity. Scientific Reports 9 (1): 1 - 9. https: // doi. org / 10.1038 / s 41598 - 019 - 54042 - z" type="journal article" year="2019">
Kellner 
<emphasis box="[726,776,598,624]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="709">et al.</emphasis>
2019
</bibRefCitation>
), we refer this taxon to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Plieninger" authorityYear="1901" box="[433,606,630,656]" pageId="28" pageNumber="707" rank="superFamily" superFamily="Pterodactyloidea">Pterodactyloidea</taxonomicName>
indet. A.
</paragraph>
